innate: present at birth but not necessarily hereditary
evoke: call forth, as an emotion, feeling, or response
concept: an abstract or general idea inferred from specific instances
account for: be the reason or explanation for
correlation: a reciprocal connection between two or more things
sequence: a following of one thing after another in time
reflect: throw or bend back from a surface
aesthetic: characterized by an appreciation of beauty or good taste
ideal: a principle or value that one hopes to attain or conform to
conformity: correspondence in form, type, or appearance
norm: a standard or model or pattern regarded as typical
assertion: a declaration that is made emphatically
desirable: worth having or seeking or achieving
restricted: subject to an act of limitation
feminine: associated with women and not with men
trait: a distinguishing feature of your personal nature
symmetrical: exhibiting equivalence or correspondence among constituents
moderate: marked by avoidance of extravagance or extremes
obsession: an unhealthy and compulsive preoccupation with something
emulate: strive to equal or match, especially by imitating
staggering: so surprisingly impressive as to stun or overwhelm
sarcasm: witty language used to convey insults or scorn
barrage: the heavy fire of artillery to saturate an area
vulnerable: capable of being wounded or hurt
shed: cause or allow to flow or run out or over
epidemic: a widespread outbreak of an infectious disease
criterion: the ideal in terms of which something can be judged
obesity: the condition of being excessively overweight
exposure: the state of being vulnerable to something
depression: a sunken or lowered geological formation
self-esteem: a feeling of pride in yourself
chronic: long-lasting or characterized by long suffering
pledge: a binding commitment to do or give or refrain from something
spur: a prod on a rider's heel used to urge a horse onward
ridicule: language or behavior intended to mock or humiliate
refute: overthrow by argument, evidence, or proof
vigorous: characterized by forceful and energetic action or activity
remedy: a medicine or therapy that cures disease or relieves pain
fad: an interest followed with exaggerated zeal
perception: the process of becoming aware through the senses
portray: represent abstractly, for example in a painting
stability: the quality or attribute of being firm and steadfast
inhibit: limit the range or extent of
efficacy: capacity or power to produce a desired result
lethal: of an instrument of certain death
feasible: capable of being done with means at hand
preliminary: preceding or in preparation for something more important
ravaged: having been robbed and destroyed by force and violence
envy: a desire to have something that is possessed by another
scorn: lack of respect accompanied by a feeling of intense dislike
stereotype: a conventional or formulaic conception or image
priority: status established in order of importance or urgency
humiliating: causing embarrassment or awareness of your shortcomings
affluent: having an abundant supply of money or possessions of value
destitute: poor enough to need help from others
interfere: get involved, so as to alter or hinder an action
mandate: a document giving an official instruction or command
extensive: large in spatial extent or range or scope or quantity
isolated: remote and separate physically or socially
spectacular: sensational in appearance or thrilling in effect
dimension: a construct distinguishing objects or individuals
homogeneous: all of the same or similar kind or nature
disparity: inequality or difference in some respect
expatriate: a person who is voluntarily absent from home or country
diaspora: the dispersion of something that was originally localized
integral: existing as an essential constituent or characteristic
obstinate: marked by tenacious unwillingness to yield
baffling: hard to comprehend, solve, or believe
hierarchy: a series of ordered groupings within a system
replicate: reproduce or make an exact copy of
eminent: standing above others in quality or position
dedicated: devoted to a cause or ideal or purpose
toxic: of or relating to or caused by a poison
glamorous: having an air of allure, romance and excitement
grudge: a resentment strong enough to justify retaliation
